        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-07-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-07-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="162"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d162">
                <head>162. Memorandum of Conversation Between President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> and Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                        >Dulles</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d162fn0">Source: Department of State,
                        Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 64 D 199. Secret. Drafted by
                            <persName>Joseph N. Greene</persName>, Jr., <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>’ Special Assistant. The meeting was held in the
                        Embassy Residence. <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> visited Ottawa July 8–11
                        for discussions with Canadian leaders. <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> and Prime Minister Diefenbaker discussed
                        disarmament and proposals for safeguards against surprise attack on July 9.
                        (Memorandum of conversation by <persName corresp="#p_MLT1"
                            >Merchant</persName>, July 9; <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> Library, <persName corresp="#p_WAC1"
                            >Whitman</persName> File, International Series, Canada) For text of the
                        joint statement issued on July 9, see <hi rend="italic">American Foreign
                            Policy: Current Documents, 1958</hi>, pp. 469–470.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Ottawa</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1958-07-10">July 10,
                            1958</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Secretary and the President discussed the growing pressure from the point of
                    view of foreign relations, on the United States Government to make some move
                    toward cessation of nuclear testing. The President said that he was disposed to
                    tell the Atomic Energy Commission that, in view of the probability that we shall
                    have to take a political decision soon, they should tack on to their present
                    Hardtack Series any additional tests that they and Defense really consider are
                    needed.</p>
            </div>
